<h1>LG Dryer Door Won't Close or Latch — Causes and How We Fix It</h1>

<p>A dryer door that won't close, latch, or stay shut stops everything — the dryer won't start without a fully closed door, and even if it somehow starts, it'll stop the moment the door pops open mid-cycle. It's one of the more straightforward repairs we do across Los Angeles County, Orange County, and Ventura County, and we almost always have the parts on the truck. The door mechanism on LG dryers has a few components that fail: the latch, the hinge, the door strike, and the seal. Most door problems are one of these, and most are fixed in a single visit of 30–60 minutes.</p>

<h2>Why a Door Problem Means the Dryer Won't Run</h2>
<p>LG dryers have a door switch — a safety interlock that cuts power to the motor and heating circuit when the door isn't fully closed. When the latch is broken or the door won't stay shut, the switch either doesn't engage (dryer won't start at all) or disengages mid-cycle (dryer stops running). This is why a broken latch feels like a much bigger problem than it is — the dryer seems completely dead when really it's a $150 latch replacement. If your dryer powers on but won't start, check the door first before assuming something more serious is wrong. A door that pops open mid-cycle is also a safety hazard — hot air venting into the laundry room and the risk of contact with a still-spinning drum. Stop using it until the door is fixed. See our <a href="/symptoms/lg-dryer-not-starting/">LG dryer not starting</a> page for the full diagnostic picture when the dryer won't respond at all.</p>

<h2>The Most Common Causes</h2>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    1. Broken or Worn Door Latch
    <span class="sev-badge sev-high">Most common</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Door closes but doesn't click or lock</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Clicking sound when closing but won't catch</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Latch tab visibly broken or missing</div>
  </div>
  <p>The door latch is the plastic strike that catches when the door closes and holds it shut. On LG DLGX and DLEX models it's a small plastic component that wears or breaks — often suddenly when someone pushes the door a bit too firmly. When it fails, the door appears to close but doesn't click into place, or you hear a clicking sound when closing but the door bounces back open within seconds. Sometimes the latch tab is visibly broken and you can see the missing piece. We carry latch assemblies for all major LG models on the truck. Cost: $150–200 including labor.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    2. Loose or Misaligned Door Strike
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Often overlooked</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Door used to close fine, now doesn't catch</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Latch tab looks intact</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Strike plate shifted position on cabinet</div>
  </div>
  <p>The door strike is the receiver on the dryer cabinet that the latch tab hooks into. Over years of use the screws holding the strike can loosen from vibration, and the strike shifts position just enough that the latch no longer lines up. The latch tab itself is fine — it's the target that moved. This is sometimes a simple adjustment rather than a replacement. We check strike position and tighten or reposition it on every door call before recommending parts. In Burbank and Pasadena we see this on machines with years of heavy use where vibration has worked the screws loose. Sometimes no new parts needed at all — just proper realignment.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    3. Worn or Bent Door Hinge
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Common on older machines</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Door sags — sits lower than it used to</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Gap visible at top when door is closed</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Handle feels loose or wobbly</div>
  </div>
  <p>The door hinge supports the weight of the door through thousands of open-and-close cycles. When the hinge wears, the door sags — and a sagging door no longer aligns properly with the latch strike on the cabinet. The latch tab hits slightly below or above where it should and the door won't close correctly. On machines 8–12 years old in Pasadena and Glendale we see this regularly. Important: a new latch won't fix a hinge problem. The door still won't align. We watch the door close slowly during diagnosis — if the tab hits below the strike, it's a hinge alignment issue, not a latch issue. When we replace hinges, we replace both simultaneously to prevent the other side from causing the same problem six months later. Cost: $180–230.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    4. Damaged Door Seal (Gasket)
    <span class="sev-badge sev-mid">Affects drying even when door closes</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Door closes but gap visible around edge</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Heat escaping during cycle</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Clothes snagging on door edge</div>
  </div>
  <p>The door seal is the felt or rubber gasket around the door opening. When it wears, tears, or falls off in sections, the door may still close and latch normally — but heat escapes through the gap, drying efficiency drops, and clothes can snag on exposed metal. A damaged seal bunched up or displaced can also physically prevent the door from closing fully. A door that doesn't seal can also cause the dryer to run hotter than normal, potentially stressing the <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-thermal-fuse-replacement/">thermal fuse</a> and <a href="/repairs/lg-dryer-heating-element-replacement/">heating element</a> over time. Cost: $150–200 for seal replacement.</p>
</div>

<div class="diag-card">
  <div class="diag-title">
    5. Something Caught in the Door Frame
    <span class="sev-badge sev-low">Check this first yourself</span>
  </div>
  <div class="diag-tags">
    <div class="diag-tag">Door suddenly won't close after a load</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Nothing visually broken</div>
    <div class="diag-tag">Feels blocked near one specific spot</div>
  </div>
  <p>Before you call us — check the door opening and drum edge for a sock, small garment, or item caught between the door and the cabinet. It happens more than people expect. A thin item caught in the door frame is enough to prevent the latch from engaging. Open the door, run your hand around the entire drum edge and door gasket area. Takes 30 seconds and is free. We get these calls in Beverly Hills and Torrance regularly — occasionally it's just a small sock from the previous load.</p>
</div>

<h2>How We Diagnose It</h2>
<p>First we check for foreign objects and look at the latch tab condition. Then we watch the door close slowly and observe where it fails — does the latch tab reach the strike, or does it hit below it? That tells us immediately whether it's a latch issue or a hinge alignment issue. We check the strike screws for looseness. We test the door switch with a multimeter — if the door has been not-latching for a while, the switch may have taken damage from repeated partial contact. And we inspect the seal for tears or displacement. Most door calls are diagnosed in under 10 minutes. We almost always have the right part on the truck.</p>

